 &= \frac{1}{m^2 + 1} \left (\frac{1}{x_1^2} + \frac{1}{x_2^2} \right) \\ &= \frac{1}{m^2 + 1} \cdot \frac{x_1^2 + x_2^2}{x_1^2 x_2^2} \\ &= \frac{1}{m^2 + 1} \cdot \frac{(x_1 + x_2)^2 - 2x_1 x_2}{(x_1 x_2)^2} \\
 &= \frac{1}{m^2 + 1} \cdot \frac{m^2 + 2c}{c^2}. \end{align}For this expression to be independent of $m,$ we must have $c = \frac{1}{2}.$  Hence, the constant $t$ is $\boxed{4}.$
